<dl id="un1013ao"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un1" href="#un1013">UN1: </a>  <a href="../../ff/unbs/un1all.htm#un1013ao"> (NLI.3) 13(ao)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <img src = "../../ff/upics/un1013ar1.png" style = "width:4%";> cup rod ball / <img src = "../../ff/upics/un1013ar2.png" style = "width:4%";> Sacred Heart / <img src = "../../ff/upics/un1013ar3.png" style = "width:4%";> virgin womb / <img src = "../../ff/upics/un1013ar4.png" style = "width:4%";> world egg</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A Noonday Vision&rdquo; 293: <img src = "../../ff/upics/un1013ar.png" style = "width:20%";> <br>This vision with its four separate pictures is called the Vision of Adoration. First is seen the <mark>cup, the rod and the ball</mark>, next is seen the <mark>sacred heart</mark>, next the <mark>virgin womb</mark>, and last the <mark>world-egg</mark>. Each in turn is formed out of the other by the unceasing play of the great life-pulse. They are aspects, moments or epochs in the ever-throbbing life of the cosmos. <small> <a name="THRdec1908" href="/udra/udex.htm#thrdec1908"><cite title="source">The Theosophical Review</cite></a> (December 1908), E. R. Innes, &ldquo;The Sign of the Sacred Heart</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c07258b" href="../../../f/ff/fnbs/c07all.htm#c07258b">VI.C.07:258(b)</a> </dd> </dd></dl>
